{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507655"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2655"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.52,0.13,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106273"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2655"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88741"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"9738"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106273"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents with a three month history of cramp-like pain in his right calf. This occurs when he walks more than 300 metres and goes away when he rests. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and has hypertension and type II diabetes. On examination, the left femoral, popliteal and dorsalis pedis pulses are all normal. The right femoral and popliteal pulses also feel normal, but the right dorsalis pedis is barely palpable. Power and sensation on both legs appear to be normal, apart from reduced sensation in both feet and weak ankle jerk reflexes. The ankle-brachial index is 1.0 on the left and 0.95 on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exercise-induced ankle-brachial index","Duplex ultrasound","CT angiogram","MR angiography","Pulse volume recording"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMeasurement of \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise-induced ankle-brachial index\u003C/strong\u003E (ABI) is the most appropriate next investigation. The history is very suggestive of intermittent claudication, but the examination findings do not bear this out. This could be because the patient has type 2 diabetes and the ABI in less reliable in these patients. The results should be viewed with caution and where possible, the lowest systolic pressure at the ankle used. Current evidence suggests that, in patients with normal or borderline resting ABIs, the next most appropriate investigation is an exercise-induced ABI. This study is performed immediately following a patient walking on a treadmill at a reasonable pace and gradient (or, if unavailable, walking up and down stairs/a hallway) and assessing their ABI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E provides a sensitive and specific (90 and 95%, respectively) means of assessing the location and degree of stenosis. However, as this patient has demonstrated normal ABIs, the next most appropriate investigation is to repeat them following exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulse volume recording\u003C/strong\u003E evaluates the arterial pressure waveform, however has fallen out of favour in place of duplex ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the ankle-brachial index is abnormal on exercise testing, then further imaging studies (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram or MR angiography\u003C/strong\u003E) might be justified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFinally, the management of cardiovascular risk factors (e.g. smoking cessation, blood pressure and serum glucose optimisation) is of great importance for secondary prevention of further vascular damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Exercise ankle-brachial indices are useful in the setting of suspected peripheral arterial disease with normal or borderline resting ankle-brachial indices.","Peripheral artery disease can present with intermittent claudication, which is characterised by cramp-like pain in the legs during exercise that resolves with rest."],"references":["Au TB, Golledge J, Walker PJ, Haigh K, Nelson M. Peripheral arterial disease - diagnosis and management in general practice. Aust Fam Physician. 2013 Jun;42(6):397-400. PMID: 23781547. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23781547/","McClary KN, Massey P. Ankle Brachial Index. [Updated 2023 Jan 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544226/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88741"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2655"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88741"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T16:32:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T16:32:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2655"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106273"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"98","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/98"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hypertension","synonyms":["Primary hypertension"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-20T08:10:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T